**Chiefs**
*   [Lallula] (d. 1807): Established the Sailo dynasty in the Lushai Hills.
*   [Lalsavunga]: Founded the original site of [Aizawl](/Aizawl).
*   [Khalkam] (d. 1891): Son of Sukpilal, organizer of the [Western Lushai Rising](/Lushai_Rising).
*   [Lalbura] (1843–1933): Son of Vanhnuailiana, organizer of the [Eastern Lushai Rising](/Lushai_Rising).
*   [Mângpawrha]: Son of Lallula, consolidated Sailo rule in the western Lushai Hills.
*   [Pâwibâwia] (1852–1892): An anti-British chief during the Lushai Expedition and Lushai Rising.
*   [Sibuta]: Notorious chief and patron of the Sibuta Lung.
*   [Suakpuilala] (d. 1881): The first and only chief to sign a sunnad with the British under Sir [John Ware Edgar](/John_Ware_Edgar).
*   [Ropuiliani] (d. 1895): A Mizo chieftainess who fiercely resisted [British colonial rule](/British_rule_in_the_Lushai_Hills).
*   [Rothangpuia]: A chief known for his friendly relations and alliance with [Thomas Herbert Lewin], participating alongside him in the [Lushai Expedition](/Lushai_Expedition).
*   [Vanhnuailiana] (d. 1871): A renowned Eastern Mizo chief.
*   [Laltheri]: A Mizo princess and poet, celebrated for her role in a tragic love story.
*   [Zakapa] (d. 1914): Organizer of the [Southern Lushai Rising](/Lushai_Rising), whose actions and legacy led to the establishment of the Zakapa award for women's achievements.

**Pasalṭha (Warriors)**
*   [Khuangchera] (d. 1890): A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) and a declared Indian freedom fighter.
*   [Taitesena] (d. 1904): A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) renowned for his volunteering and hunting prowess.
*   [Saizahawla] (b. 1858): A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) celebrated for his wrestling and athletic abilities.
*   [Chawngbawla]: A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) known for his participation in the [North-South War of the Lushai Hills](/North-South_War_of_the_Lushai_Hills).
*   [Zampuimanga]: A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) who served [Lalsavunga](/Lalsavunga) and was known for hunting tigers.
*   [Vana Pa]: A Mizo [Pasalṭha](/Pasal%E1%B9%ADha) recognized for his tactical acumen and counsel; Vanapa Hall is named in his honor.